--- !u!114 &687007694
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 687007693}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 2a790c3bc2ab59f4f95fce7b0f797629, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  basliklar:
  - How a DC Motor Works
  - 1. Frame (Housing)
  - 2. Stator
  - 3. Rotor (Armature)
  - 4. Armature Windings
  - 5. Commutator
  - 6. Brushes
  - 7. Shaft
  - 8. Bearings
  - 9. End Covers (End Bells)
  aciklamalar:
  - When electric current flows into the motor, it enters through the brushes. The
    current passes through the commutator and into the armature windings.  The magnetic
    field from the stator interacts with the magnetic field in the rotor. This interaction
    creates torque and causes the rotor to spin.  The spinning rotor turns the shaft.
    The shaft delivers mechanical energy to an external load.
  - The frame, also called the housing, is the outer body of the DC motor. It is
    usually made of metal. The frame protects the motor from dust, dirt, and physical
    damage.  All the other motor parts are placed inside the frame. The frame keeps
    the motor strong and stable during operation. It also helps remove heat that
    is produced while the motor is running.
  - The stator is the stationary part of the motor. It does not move during operation. 
    The stator creates a magnetic field inside the motor. This magnetic field is
    very important because it allows the motor to work.  In DC motors, the stator
    can be made of permanent magnets or coils. The magnetic field produced by the
    stator interacts with the rotor.
  - The rotor, also called the armature, is the rotating part of the motor. It is
    located at the center of the motor. The rotor is mounted on the shaft and spins
    when the motor is powered.  When electric current flows through the rotor, it
    reacts with the magnetic field. This reaction creates a force that makes the
    rotor turn. The movement of the rotor is what produces mechanical energy.
  - "Armature windings are copper wires wrapped around the rotor. These wires carry
    electric current from the power supply.  When current flows through the windings,
    a magnetic field is created. This magnetic field interacts with the stator\u2019s
    magnetic field.  The interaction between these two magnetic fields creates torque.
    Torque is the force that causes the rotor to rotate."
  - The commutator is a cylindrical part attached to the rotor shaft. It is made
    of copper segments separated by insulation.  The main function of the commutator
    is to change the direction of current. This change happens at the correct time
    during rotation.  By changing the current direction, the commutator keeps the
    rotor spinning in one direction. Without the commutator, the motor would not
    rotate smoothly.
  - Brushes are small blocks made of carbon or graphite. They are fixed in place
    and do not rotate.  The brushes touch the surface of the commutator. They allow
    electric current to flow from the power source into the rotor.  As the rotor
    spins, the brushes stay in contact with the commutator. This ensures a continuous
    supply of electricity to the motor.
  - "The shaft is a metal rod connected to the rotor. It rotates together with the
    rotor.  The shaft transfers the motor\u2019s rotation to external devices. These
    devices can be wheels, fans, gears, or machines.  The shaft extends outside the
    motor housing so the motor can do useful work."
  - Bearings are placed around the shaft at both ends of the motor. They support
    the shaft and keep it aligned.  Bearings reduce friction between moving and stationary
    parts. This helps the motor rotate smoothly and efficiently.  Good bearings increase
    motor life and reduce noise and vibration.
  - End covers are located at the front and back of the motor. They are attached
    to the frame.  End covers hold the bearings in position. They also help keep
    the shaft properly aligned.  In addition, end covers protect the internal parts
    of the motor from dust and damage.
